1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
So, what happens if, from one day to the next, the prison gates open and more than 20,000 people are set free?

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:09,000
It sounds like the beginning of a movie, doesn't it?

3
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:13,000
Yet it really happened in Italy in 2006.

4
00:00:13,000 --> 00:00:18,000
It was an incredible experiment, although not entirely intentional.

5
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:23,000
And today we're going to do just that, an investigation, to understand what this event has taught us

6
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:26,000
and to answer a fundamental question about crime.

7
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:31,000
And the question, the mystery at the center of our investigation, is precisely this.

8
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:34,000
But prison, how does it reduce crime?

9
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:38,000
Does it work because, you know, it scares people, discourages them from committing crimes,

10
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:42,000
or is its effectiveness much more down-to-earth, much more practical,

11
00:00:42,000 --> 00:00:45,000
meaning simply that those who are inside cannot commit crimes outside?

12
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:47,000
It's quite a dilemma, isn't it?

13
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:52,000
Exactly, look, in criminology there are precisely these two key concepts.

14
00:00:52,000 --> 00:00:56,000
On one hand, there's deterrence, which is the idea that the threat of prison

15
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:59,000
is scary enough to stop potential criminals.

16
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:03,000
On the other hand, there's incapacitation, which is, let's say, much more direct.

17
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:07,000
If you're in jail, quite simply, you can't go around committing robberies.

18
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:11,000
Well, that's exactly where the 2006 pardon becomes so interesting.

19
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Because it offered us, on a silver platter, a crazy opportunity

20
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:20,000
to test these two theories and see which one weighs more in reality.

21
00:01:20,000 --> 00:01:25,000
Because to solve a case you need evidence, and incredibly, Italy in 2006

22
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:30,000
became a sort of perfect crime scene for scholars.

23
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:35,000
What happened created the conditions for a so-called natural experiment,

24
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,000
practically an open-air laboratory for studying crime.

25
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:42,000
To understand why it came to this, we need to take a step back

26
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:46,000
and look at the situation of Italian prisons in those years.

27
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:48,000
We're talking about a truly explosive situation.

28
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:53,000
The system was literally collapsing, with overcrowding that had been going on for years

29
00:01:53,000 --> 00:01:57,000
and which had made living conditions inside simply unsustainable.

30
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:03,000
And to give a concrete idea, one number is enough: 138% in June 2006,

31
00:02:03,000 --> 00:02:06,000
that was the prison occupancy rate.

32
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Imagine 100 available spots and 138 people occupying them.

33
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:13,000
It was a time bomb, that was clear.

34
00:02:13,000 --> 00:02:17,000
And at that point, the government realized it had to do something, and something drastic.

35
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:20,000
And indeed, here is the timeline of events.

36
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:23,000
Pressure rises, rises, rises for years.

37
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,000
And in July 2006, the decision arrives: the pardon.

38
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:30,000
A month later, in August, the unthinkable happens.

39
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:35,000
Thousands upon thousands of inmates leave prison practically all at once.

40
00:02:35,000 --> 00:02:38,000
It was a huge, sudden shock for the entire system.

41
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:41,000
And from a scientific point of view, something measurable.

42
00:02:41,000 --> 00:02:46,000
But let's talk about the scope of this shock, because it's staggering.

43
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:51,000
In just one month, the prison population dropped by 36%.

44
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:52,000
Let's think about it for a moment.

45
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:56,000
It's as if more than a third of the prisons had emptied out all at once.

46
00:02:56,000 --> 00:03:02,000
Something never seen before, which obviously created an incredible set of data for our investigation.

47
00:03:02,000 --> 00:03:05,000
Okay, so we have the crime scene.

48
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:07,000
We have the motive, so to speak.

49
00:03:07,000 --> 00:03:10,000
Now, as in any investigation worth its salt,

50
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:12,000
it's time to analyze the evidence.

51
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:16,000
The researchers who studied this case followed three leads,

52
00:03:16,000 --> 00:03:20,000
three fundamental clues to understand what really happened.

53
00:03:20,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Exactly, those are the three questions they tried to answer.

54
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:29,000
First, what happened to crime in the short term, immediately after the release?

55
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:32,000
Second, what happened later?

56
00:03:32,000 --> 00:03:35,000
As the prisons began to fill up again.

57
00:03:35,000 --> 00:03:41,000
And third, very importantly, was the impact the same everywhere in Italy

58
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:44,000
or did it change from province to province?

59
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:48,000
So, let's start with the first clue: the immediate impact.

60
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:50,000
Here the evidence is almost overwhelming.

61
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:53,000
If you look at crime data at the national level,

62
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:55,000
you see a clear break, a step.

63
00:03:55,000 --> 00:03:59,000
Exactly in correspondence with the mass release of August 2006,

64
00:03:59,000 --> 00:04:01,000
crimes take a leap upwards.

65
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:03,000
It's an almost perfect correlation.

66
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,000
And this graph shows it clearly.

67
00:04:06,000 --> 00:04:09,000
Look at the difference between before the pardon, in July,

68
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:11,000
and immediately after, in September.

69
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:12,000
There's a surge.

70
00:04:12,000 --> 00:04:16,000
And we're talking mainly about crimes like thefts and robberies.

71
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:18,000
The increase is so rapid, so clear,

72
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:23,000
that it's practically impossible not to link it directly to the pardon.

73
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:26,000
Good, let's move on to the second clue.

74
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:29,000
After that massive emptying, the prisons, obviously,

75
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:31,000
started to fill up again,

76
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:33,000
but here there is a key detail.

77
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:37,000
It wasn't so much the former inmates coming back in who filled them,

78
00:04:37,000 --> 00:04:39,000
but rather new criminals,

79
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:41,000
people who were being arrested for the first time.

80
00:04:41,000 --> 00:04:43,000
And this is very interesting.

81
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:46,000
Yes, because here a fact comes out that's a bit surprising.

82
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:48,000
By analyzing precisely these new entries,

83
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:50,000
researchers made a calculation

84
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:53,000
and discovered that their incapacitation effect

85
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,000
was actually greater.

86
00:04:55,000 --> 00:04:58,000
Basically, every new inmate who took the place of an old one,

87
00:04:58,000 --> 00:04:59,000
let's put it that way,

88
00:04:59,000 --> 00:05:02,000
prevented up to 46 crimes per year.

89
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:04,000
This tells us something important.

90
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:07,000
On average, this new group was criminally more prolific

91
00:05:07,000 --> 00:05:09,000
than the ones who had been released.

92
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:12,000
And we come to the third and final clue,

93
00:05:12,000 --> 00:05:14,000
which is perhaps the most illuminating.

94
00:05:14,000 --> 00:05:18,000
Here the investigation shifts, zooming in from national to local.

95
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:22,000
Researchers examined all 103 Italian provinces

96
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:24,000
and looked at two things.

97
00:05:24,000 --> 00:05:27,000
How many pardoned inmates returned to that specific province

98
00:05:27,000 --> 00:05:30,000
and how crime changed there.

99
00:05:30,000 --> 00:05:33,000
And here, in my opinion, is the real turning point.

100
00:05:33,000 --> 00:05:35,000
A very clear pattern emerged.

101
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:37,000
In provinces that, even before the pardon,

102
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:39,000
had high incarceration rates,

103
00:05:39,000 --> 00:05:42,000
the increase in crimes for each released inmate

104
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:44,000
was lower.

105
00:05:44,000 --> 00:05:46,000
The fishing analogy fits perfectly.

106
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:47,000
If you fish in a lake,

107
00:05:47,000 --> 00:05:49,000
at the beginning you catch the biggest fish,

108
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:50,000
the easiest ones,

109
00:05:50,000 --> 00:05:52,000
but the more you continue fishing,

110
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:53,000
the harder it gets,

111
00:05:53,000 --> 00:05:55,000
and for every hour of effort, you get less.

112
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:57,000
In economics, this is called

113
00:05:57,000 --> 00:05:59,000
the law of diminishing returns

114
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:01,000
and apparently it also applies to incarceration.

115
00:06:01,000 --> 00:06:04,000
At this point, with all three clues on the table,

116
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:06,000
we can deliver our verdict

117
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:08,000
and the conclusion to which this investigation

118
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:10,000
leads us is powerful

119
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:13,000
and in some ways also a bit counterintuitive,

120
00:06:13,000 --> 00:06:16,000
regarding how prison actually works.

121
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:19,000
The verdict of the study, the scientific one,

122
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:21,000
is perfectly summarized in this sentence.

123
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,000
The crime prevention effects

124
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:25,000
of incarceration decrease

125
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:27,000
as the incarceration rate increases.

126
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:30,000
That's the heart of the whole discovery.

127
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:31,000
Exactly!

128
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:34,000
If we want to put it in simple terms, it means this:

129
00:06:34,000 --> 00:06:36,000
putting people in prison

130
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:38,000
to prevent them from committing crimes,

131
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:41,000
incapacitation works, no doubt about it,

132
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:43,000
but there is a "but."

133
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:45,000
Its effect is not always the same.

134
00:06:45,000 --> 00:06:47,000
In fact, the more people you put inside,

135
00:06:47,000 --> 00:06:49,000
the less effective it becomes,

136
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:50,000
with every new arrest.

137
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:51,000
It's logical.

138
00:06:51,000 --> 00:06:53,000
The first ones you take out of circulation

139
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:55,000
are the most active criminals,

140
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:56,000
but as you go on,

141
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:57,000
you end up incarcerating

142
00:06:57,000 --> 00:06:59,000
increasingly less dangerous people.

143
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:01,000
But wait,

144
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:03,000
the investigation isn't quite closed yet.

145
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:04,000
There's one last part,

146
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:06,000
a sort of plot twist.

147
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:08,000
Besides all this,

148
00:07:08,000 --> 00:07:09,000
we must ask ourselves,

149
00:07:09,000 --> 00:07:12,000
from a purely economic point of view,

150
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:15,000
was the pardon a worthwhile move?

151
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:16,000
Precisely,

152
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:18,000
it's time for the cost-benefit analysis.

153
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:19,000
On one hand,

154
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:21,000
we have the money saved by the state,

155
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:22,000
on the other,

156
00:07:22,000 --> 00:07:24,000
the costs that society had to pay,

157
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:27,000
which of the two sides of the scale weighs more?

158
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:29,000
Well, let's start with the benefits.

159
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,000
The calculation is quite straightforward.

160
00:07:31,000 --> 00:07:32,000
By no longer having to provide

161
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:34,000
food, lodging, and surveillance

162
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:36,000
for over 25,000 people,

163
00:07:36,000 --> 00:07:38,000
the Italian state saved

164
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:39,000
a considerable amount.

165
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:42,000
We're talking about approximately 245 million euros.

166
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:44,000
And now, the costs.

167
00:07:44,000 --> 00:07:46,000
And here, the figure is,

168
00:07:46,000 --> 00:07:48,000
well, it's of another order of magnitude.

169
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:50,000
The social costs,

170
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:52,000
meaning the value of all the additional crimes

171
00:07:52,000 --> 00:07:54,000
committed by those who were released,

172
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:55,000
have been estimated

173
00:07:55,000 --> 00:07:58,000
at up to 2.2 billion euros.

174
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:00,000
It's a huge figure,

175
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:02,000
that pales in comparison to the state savings.

176
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:04,000
So in the end,

177
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,000
the investigation into the 2006 pardon

178
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:09,000
leaves us with a very important question.

179
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:11,000
It showed us that yes,

180
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:13,000
incapacitation works,

181
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:15,000
but not infinitely,

182
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:16,000
and that political decisions

183
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:18,000
in this field have enormous

184
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:20,000
economic and social consequences.

185
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:22,000
The real question, then,

186
00:08:22,000 --> 00:08:24,000
is what is the right balance point

187
00:08:24,000 --> 00:08:26,000
between costs and safety;

188
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:27,000
there is no easy answer,

189
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:29,000
and it is probably one of the

190
00:08:29,000 --> 00:08:32,000
most complex challenges for any country.